    <body>
      <div xml:id="NA74-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu talaivi pāṇarkku (EN, EV: pāṇaṟku) vāyiṉ maṟuttatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is how SHE refused the door to the bard.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA74">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            vaṭikkatir tiritta vaṉñāṭ peruvalai</l>
<l>            yiṭikkuraṟ puṇarip pauvat tiṭumār</l>
<l>            niṟaiyap peyta vampi kāḻōr</l>
<l>            ciṟaiyaruṅ kaḷiṟṟiṟ paratava royyum</l>
<l>            ciṟuvī ñāḻaṟ peruṅkaṭaṟ cērppaṉai </l>
<l>            yēti lāḷaṉu meṉpa pōtaviḻ</l>
<l>            putumaṇaṟ kāṉaṟ puṉṉai nuṇṭātu</l>
<l>            koṇṭa lacaivaḷi tūkkutoṟuṅ kurukiṉ</l>
<l>            veṇpuṟa mākiya vārkkun teṇkaṭaṟ</l>
<l>            kaṇṭal vēliya vūravaṉ </l>
<l>            peṇṭeṉa vaṟintaṉṟu peyarttalō varitē.</l>
            </lg>
       <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>The man from the coast of the great sea with small-blossomed Ñāḻal trees,</l>
<l rend="indent2">where the fishermen carry, like elephant bulls hard to restrain</l>
<l rend="indent2">by the rod-bearer, the small boats, fully laden(?)<note place="foot">The phrase <term xml:lang="ta">niṟaiya peyta</term> is syntactically unclear. T.V.G. explains that the nets fill the boats, which seems sensible.</note>, in order to</l>
<l rend="indent2">put [their] big nets with strong strings fashioned by the spindle(?)</l>
<l rend="indent2">into the ocean with waves of thundering voice,</l>
<l>he [is] a stranger, they say.</l>
<l>It is known to the village with mangrove fences by the clear sea,</l>
<l rend="indent">where the Puṉṉai trees of the seashore-grove in the new sand,</l>
<l rend="indent3">which have opened [their] buds,</l>
<l rend="indent">pour fine pollen with every thrust of the cloud-moving wind,</l>
<l rend="indent2">for the backs of the herons to become white,</l>
<l><choice>
    <seg>that [I am] his wife</seg>
    <seg>that [she is] his wife<note place="foot">T.V.G. takes the poem along the lines of the <term xml:lang="ta">kiḷavi</term>: SHE would refuse the mediation of the bard, because HIS relation to the other woman is publicly known. The wording can as well refer to the usual premarital situation: the village has found out about THEIR secret relation, and does not think HE is suitable.</note></seg>
   </choice>
   – [a fact] hard to obliterate.<note place="foot">Literally: <term xml:lang="ta">peyarttalō aritē</term> “as for removing [that knowledge from public consciousness], it is difficult”.</note></l>
        </lg>
         </div>
